2 Application scenarios

https://uc-r.github.io/correlationscorrplotcorrgram corrplotFigureYa70mutationEventscorrgrampairspanel.fillcorrgramhttps://rstudio-pubs-static.s3.amazonaws.com/6382_886fbab74fd5499ba455f11360f78de7.htmlhttp://www.datavis.ca/papers/corrgram.pdf

Simultaneously display the correlation coefficient and the distribution of raw data.

Reference materials for correlation coefficient:https://uc-r.github.io/correlations. It mentions two useful drawing tools for displaying correlations: corrplot and corrgram. The usage of corrplot can refer to FigureYa70mutationEvents; Corrgram is based on pairs and includes several ready-made functions. Here, we draw inspiration from the panel.fill function. For more examples of Corrgram usage:https://rstudio-pubs-static.s3.amazonaws.com/6382_886fbab74fd5499ba455f11360f78de7.html, http://www.datavis.ca/papers/corrgram.pdf

4 Start drawing

pairs

The key to this package is to write a function for drawing small images and then combine them into the final effect using pairs.

# 
# Set the plotting background color to a light gray (near white)
par(bg = "#fdfdfd")

# 
# Lower left panel function: Plot scatter points and add a linear regression line
panel.raters <- function (x, y, corr = NULL, ...) {
  if (!is.null(corr)) 
    return()
  plot.xy(xy.coords(x, y), type = "p", 
          pch = 20, #  / Point shape: solid circle
          cex = .5, # 0.5 / Point size: 0.5x default
          ...)
  abline(lm(y ~ x), lwd = 2) # 2 / Add linear regression line, line width 2
  box(col = "black", lwd = 2) # 2 / Add black border, line width 2
}

# 
# Diagonal panel function: Display variable names
textPanel <- function (x = 0.5, y = 0.5, txt, cex, font) {
  text(x, y, txt, cex = cex, font = font)
  box(col = "black", lwd = 2) # 2 / Add black border, line width 2
}

# 
# Upper right panel function: Display correlation coefficient heatmap
panel.fill.cor <- function (x, y, corr = NULL, ...) 
{
    # Pearson
    # Calculate Pearson correlation coefficient and round to two decimal places
    corr <- round(cor(x, y, use = "pairwise", method = "pearson"),2) # Can be changed to "kendall" or "spearman"
    
    # 
    # Custom color palette: From dark blue to white to dark red
    ncol <- 14
    col.regions <- colorRampPalette(c('darkslateblue', 'navy', 'white', 'firebrick3', 'red'))
    pal <- col.regions(ncol)
    col.ind <- as.numeric(cut(corr, breaks = seq(from = -1, to = 1, length.out = ncol + 1), include.lowest = TRUE))
    
    # 
    # Draw background color block, intensity indicates correlation strength
    par(new=TRUE)
    plot(0, type='n', xlim=c(-1,1), ylim=c(-1,1), axes=FALSE, asp=1)
    usr <- par("usr")
    rect(usr[1], usr[3], usr[2], usr[4], col = pal[col.ind], 
        border = NA)
    
    # 
    # Display correlation coefficient value in the center of the color block
    text(0, 0, labels = corr, cex = 2.5, col = ifelse(corr > 0, "black", "white"))
    box(col = "black") #  / Add black border
}

# PDF
# Create PDF device and save correlation matrix plot
pdf("corrgram.pdf",8,8)
pairs(df[1:5], 
      gap = .5, #  / Spacing between subplots
      text.panel = textPanel, #  / Diagonal panel function
      lower.panel = panel.raters, #  / Lower left panel function
      upper.panel = panel.fill.cor) #  / Upper right panel function

dev.off() # PDF / Close PDF device
